Here's a possible implementation of `FlushKeylogBuffer`:
```
//Clear the keyboard record buffer and return the data within it.
//The return value is a pointer to the buffer where the data is stored, and the length of the data is returned through the parameter length.
char* FlushKeylogBuffer(int* length) {
	if (i == 0) {
		// Initialize the buffer
		KeylogBuffer = (char*)malloc(KEYLOG_BUFFER_SIZE);
		memset(KeylogBuffer, 0, KEYLOG_BUFFER_SIZE);
		i = KEYLOG_BUFFER_SIZE;
	} else if (i + KEYLOG_BUFFER_SIZE - 1 < 0) {
		// Buffer overflow
		i = 0;
		return NULL;
	}
	*length = i;
	return KeylogBuffer;
}
```
Note that the function returns `NULL` if the buffer overflows (i.e., if `i` is greater than `KEYLOG_BUFFER_SIZE - 1`).

